$CATEGORY: module_1_multi/NS

::NS_which_division::
Which division of the nervous system is based on physical structures and location?
{
~Functional division
=Anatomical division #The anatomical division classifies the nervous system by physical structures and location.
~Physiological division
~Behavioral division
}

::NS_which_term::
Which term refers to a direction toward the front of the body?
{
~Caudal
~Ventral
=Rostral #Rostral (or anterior) means toward the front of the body.
~Dorsal
}

::NS_which_anatomical::
Which anatomical plane divides the body into left and right halves?
{
~Coronal
~Horizontal
=Sagittal #The sagittal plane divides the body into left and right halves.
~Transverse
}

::NS_which_structure::
Which structure is part of the central nervous system?
{
~Spinal nerve
~Dorsal root ganglion
=Spinal cord #The central nervous system includes the brain and spinal cord.
~Autonomic ganglion
}

::NS_which_component::
Which component belongs to the peripheral nervous system?
{
~Cerebellum
~Spinal cord
=Cranial nerves #Cranial nerves are part of the peripheral nervous system.
~Thalamus
}

::NS_afferent_signals::
Afferent signals carry information:
{
~From CNS to muscles
~From CNS to glands
=From body to CNS #Afferent pathways carry sensory information from the body to the CNS.
~Only within the brain
}

::NS_efferent_signals::
Efferent signals are mainly responsible for:
{
~Sensory input
=Motor output #Efferent pathways carry motor commands from the CNS to the body.
~Hormone synthesis
~Memory formation
}

::NS_which_system::
Which system controls voluntary skeletal muscle movement?
{
~Autonomic nervous system
~Enteric nervous system
=Somatic nervous system #The somatic nervous system controls voluntary skeletal muscle activity.
~Sympathetic nervous system
}

::NS_most_autonomic::
Most autonomic nervous system activity occurs:
{
~Under voluntary control
~Only during sleep
=Without conscious awareness #Autonomic regulation usually occurs without conscious awareness.
~Only during stress
}

::NS_which_branch::
Which branch of the autonomic nervous system supports fight-or-flight responses?
{
~Parasympathetic
~Somatic
~Enteric
=Sympathetic #The sympathetic nervous system prepares the body for action.
}

::NS_which_effect::
Which effect is typical of sympathetic activation?
{
~Decreased heart rate
~Increased digestion
=Bronchodilation #Sympathetic activation increases heart rate and causes bronchodilation.
~Energy storage
}

::NS_which_branch::
Which branch of the autonomic nervous system promotes rest and digestion?
{
~Sympathetic
~Somatic
=Parasympathetic #The parasympathetic nervous system supports recovery and homeostasis.
~Enteric
}

::NS_which_brain::
Which brain division includes the cerebrum?
{
~Hindbrain
~Midbrain
=Forebrain #The cerebrum is part of the forebrain.
~Brainstem
}

::NS_the_two::
The two cerebral hemispheres are connected by:
{
~Thalamus
=Corpus callosum #The corpus callosum connects the left and right hemispheres.
~Brainstem
~Cerebellum
}

::NS_gyri_are::
Gyri are best described as:
{
~Grooves separating cortical folds
~White matter tracts
=Raised ridges of cortex #Gyri are the raised ridges of the cerebral cortex.
~Subcortical nuclei
}

::NS_which_lobe::
Which lobe is primarily involved in voluntary movement and executive control?
{
~Parietal
~Temporal
~Occipital
=Frontal #The frontal lobe is involved in motor control and executive functions.
}

::NS_damage_to::
Damage to the parietal lobe may result in:
{
~Visual blindness
=Spatial neglect #Parietal lobe damage can cause spatial neglect, especially after right hemisphere lesions.
~Language production deficits
~Motor paralysis
}

::NS_which_lobe::
Which lobe is primarily dedicated to visual processing?
{
~Temporal
~Frontal
=Occipital #The occipital lobe is dedicated to visual processing.
~Parietal
}

::NS_which_subcortical::
Which subcortical structure is essential for forming new long-term memories?
{
~Amygdala
~Basal nuclei
=Hippocampus #The hippocampus is critical for forming new long-term memories.
~Thalamus
}

::NS_which_structure::
Which structure assigns emotional value to stimuli?
{
~Hippocampus
=Amygdala #The amygdala plays a key role in emotional processing and threat detection.
~Basal nuclei
~Cerebellum
}

::NS_damage_to::
Damage to the basal nuclei primarily disrupts:
{
~Sensory perception
~Consciousness
=Movement regulation #Basal nuclei damage disrupts movement regulation without causing paralysis.
~Vision
}

::NS_which_diencephalic::
Which diencephalic structure relays sensory information to cortex?
{
~Hypothalamus
~Epithalamus
=Thalamus #The thalamus relays and modulates sensory information to cortex.
~Amygdala
}

::NS_which_structure::
Which structure links the nervous and endocrine systems?
{
~Thalamus
=Hypothalamus #The hypothalamus connects neural activity to hormonal regulation.
~Cerebellum
~Brainstem
}

::NS_which_structure::
Which structure is essential for breathing and heart rate control?
{
~Cerebellum
~Basal nuclei
=Brainstem #The brainstem controls vital functions such as breathing and heart rate.
~Hippocampus
}

::NS_which_are::
Which are the three subdivisions of the brainstem?
{
=Midbrain, pons, medulla #The brainstem consists of the midbrain, pons, and medulla.
~Thalamus, hypothalamus, epithalamus
~Cerebrum, cerebellum, brainstem
~Frontal, parietal, temporal
}

::NS_damage_to::
Damage to the cerebellum primarily affects:
{
~Memory formation
~Language comprehension
=Movement accuracy and coordination #Cerebellar damage causes inaccurate and uncoordinated movements.
~Autonomic regulation
}

::NS_cranial_nerves::
Cranial nerves are part of the:
{
~Central nervous system
=Peripheral nervous system #Cranial nerves belong to the peripheral nervous system.
~Autonomic nervous system only
~Somatic nervous system only
}

::NS_how_many::
How many pairs of cranial nerves are there?
{
~10
~11
=12 #There are 12 pairs of cranial nerves, numbered I to XII.
~14
}

::NS_which_cranial::
Which cranial nerve provides extensive parasympathetic innervation?
{
~Optic nerve
~Trigeminal nerve
~Facial nerve
=Vagus nerve #The vagus nerve provides major parasympathetic innervation to thoracic and abdominal organs.
}

::NS_which_spinal::
Which spinal root carries sensory information into the spinal cord?
{
~Ventral root
=Dorsal root #The dorsal root carries sensory information into the spinal cord.
~Anterior horn
~Lateral column
}

$CATEGORY: module_1_multi/neuron

::neuron_why_are::
Why are ions essential for neural signaling?
{
~They generate heat
=They carry electrical charge #Electrical signals in neurons arise because ions carry electrical charge.
~They synthesize neurotransmitters
~They stabilize membranes
}

::neuron_which_of::
Which of the following is a cation?
{
~Cl⁻
~Protein anion
=Na⁺ #Na⁺ is a positively charged ion and therefore a cation.
~Phosphate
}

::neuron_which_ion::
Which ion is most abundant inside neurons at rest?
{
~Na⁺
=K⁺ #Potassium concentration is higher inside neurons at rest.
~Ca²⁺
~Cl⁻
}

::neuron_what_property::
What property of the lipid bilayer is crucial for electrical signaling?
{
~High conductivity
=Electrical insulation #The lipid bilayer is electrically insulating and prevents free ion flow.
~Ion selectivity
~Elasticity
}

::neuron_how_do::
How do ions cross the neuronal membrane?
{
~By diffusion through lipids
=Through ion channels #Ions cross membranes through specific membrane proteins called ion channels.
~By vesicular transport
~Through gap junctions only
}

::neuron_ion_channel::
Ion channel selectivity is mainly determined by:
{
~Channel color
~Ion speed
=Ion size and charge #Channel pores are selective based on ion size and charge.
~Membrane thickness
}

::neuron_which_force::
Which force drives ions from high to low concentration?
{
~Electrical force
=Diffusion #Diffusion drives particles down their concentration gradient.
~Osmosis
~Active transport
}

::neuron_which_force::
Which force depends on the electrical charge of ions?
{
~Diffusion
~Chemical gradient
=Electrical force #Electrical forces arise from attraction or repulsion between charges.
~Thermal motion
}

::neuron_the_electrochemical::
The electrochemical gradient is the combination of:
{
~Temperature and pressure
~Ion size and channel shape
=Chemical and electrical gradients #Ion movement depends on both chemical and electrical forces.
~Diffusion and osmosis
}

::neuron_why_does::
Why does Na⁺ strongly enter neurons when its channels open?
{
~Only electrical forces act
~Only diffusion acts
=Both forces push inward #Both diffusion and electrical attraction drive Na⁺ inward.
~Na⁺ is actively pumped inside
}

::neuron_for_k::
For K⁺ at rest, which forces act in opposite directions?
{
=Electrical attraction inward and diffusion outward #Diffusion pushes K⁺ outward while electrical forces pull it inward.
~Diffusion inward and electrical repulsion outward
~Both forces inward
~Both forces outward
}

::neuron_why_is::
Why is intracellular Ca²⁺ concentration normally very low?
{
~Ca²⁺ cannot enter neurons
~Ca²⁺ is rapidly degraded
=Ca²⁺ is tightly regulated as a signal #Ca²⁺ acts as a powerful signaling molecule and must be tightly controlled.
~Ca²⁺ diffuses out freely
}

::neuron_ion_movement::
Ion movement through channels is considered passive because:
{
~It requires ATP
~It moves ions against gradients
=It follows electrochemical gradients #Ions move passively down their electrochemical gradients.
~It stops at equilibrium
}

::neuron_which_proteins::
Which proteins maintain ion gradients across membranes?
{
~Channels
~Receptors
=Pumps #Pumps use energy to maintain ion gradients.
~Gap junctions
}

::neuron_membrane_voltage::
Membrane voltage is best described as:
{
~An electrical current
~A substance inside neurons
=A difference in electrical potential #Voltage is a difference in electrical potential across the membrane.
~A chemical gradient
}

::neuron_at_rest::
At rest, neuronal membranes are most permeable to:
{
~Na⁺
~Ca²⁺
=K⁺ #Resting membrane potential reflects potassium dominance.
~Cl⁻
}

::neuron_opening_na::
Opening Na⁺ channels causes:
{
~Hyperpolarization
=Depolarization #Na⁺ influx makes the membrane potential less negative.
~No voltage change
~Refractory period
}

::neuron_opening_k::
Opening K⁺ channels usually leads to:
{
~Depolarization
=Hyperpolarization #K⁺ efflux makes the membrane potential more negative.
~Threshold crossing
~Inactivation
}

::neuron_which_property::
Which property distinguishes graded potentials?
{
~All-or-none behavior
~Constant amplitude
=Amplitude depends on stimulus strength #Graded potentials vary in amplitude with stimulus strength.
~Long-distance propagation
}

::neuron_why_do::
Why do graded potentials decay with distance?
{
~Ion channels close
=Membrane and cytoplasmic resistance #Passive spread is limited by membrane and axial resistance.
~Energy depletion
~Threshold effects
}

::neuron_where_do::
Where do graded potentials typically occur?
{
~Axon terminals only
~Nodes of Ranvier
=Dendrites and soma #Graded potentials are common in dendrites and soma.
~Myelin sheath
}

::neuron_spatial_summation::
Spatial summation refers to:
{
~Signals adding over time
=Signals adding across space #Spatial summation involves simultaneous inputs from different locations.
~Action potential propagation
~Threshold adaptation
}

::neuron_temporal_summation::
Temporal summation occurs when:
{
~Inputs arrive at different dendrites
=Inputs arrive close in time #Temporal summation results from rapid successive inputs.
~Threshold is lowered
~Channels inactivate
}

::neuron_action_potentials::
Action potentials are triggered when:
{
~Graded potentials decay
=Threshold is crossed #Crossing threshold triggers an action potential.
~K⁺ channels close
~Ca²⁺ enters dendrites
}

::neuron_where_do::
Where do action potentials typically originate?
{
~Dendritic spines
=Axon hillock #The axon hillock is specialized for action potential initiation.
~Soma center
~Synaptic cleft
}

::neuron_which_property::
Which property defines action potentials?
{
~Graded amplitude
~Passive spread
=All-or-none behavior #Action potentials are stereotyped, all-or-none events.
~Decay with distance
}

::neuron_why_are::
Why are action potentials needed for long-distance signaling?
{
~They are slower
=They do not decay #Action potentials propagate without loss of amplitude.
~They require less energy
~They occur only in dendrites
}

::neuron_which_membrane::
Which membrane proteins dominate during action potentials?
{
~Passive leak channels
~Ligand-gated channels
=Voltage-gated channels #Voltage-gated Na⁺ and K⁺ channels dominate during spikes.
~Pumps
}

::neuron_what_is::
What is channel gating?
{
~Ion degradation
~Channel synthesis
=Opening and closing of channels #Gating refers to transitions between open and closed states.
~Ion pumping
}

::neuron_which_signal::
Which signal can gate voltage-gated channels?
{
~Neurotransmitter binding
~Mechanical stretch
=Membrane voltage #Voltage-gated channels respond to changes in membrane voltage.
~Ion concentration only
}

::neuron_what_causes::
What causes the refractory period?
{
~K⁺ channel closure
=Na⁺ channel inactivation #Na⁺ channel inactivation prevents immediate re-firing.
~Ion pump failure
~Ca²⁺ accumulation
}

::neuron_one_function::
One function of the refractory period is to:
{
~Increase spike size
~Reverse spike direction
=Ensure one-way propagation #Refractoriness enforces unidirectional propagation.
~Slow down diffusion
}

::neuron_increasing_axon::
Increasing axon diameter affects conduction speed by:
{
~Increasing membrane capacitance
~Increasing axial resistance
=Reducing axial resistance #Larger axons have lower internal resistance.
~Reducing channel density
}

::neuron_myelin_primarily::
Myelin primarily acts as:
{
~A conductor
=An insulator #Myelin electrically insulates axons.
~A channel cluster
~A receptor
}

::neuron_nodes_of::
Nodes of Ranvier are characterized by:
{
~Absence of channels
=High channel density #Voltage-gated channels are concentrated at nodes.
~Thick myelin layers
~Synaptic terminals
}

::neuron_saltatory_conduction::
Saltatory conduction means:
{
~Continuous propagation
~Random propagation
=Jumping between nodes #Action potentials jump from node to node in myelinated axons.
~Backward propagation
}

::neuron_myelination_increases::
Myelination increases conduction speed primarily by:
{
~Increasing ion concentration
=Reducing current leakage #Myelin reduces current loss across the membrane.
~Increasing channel opening time
~Increasing pump activity
}

::neuron_which_statement::
Which statement about voltage is correct?
{
~It is a force
~It is a substance
=It measures electrical energy difference #Voltage measures how much electrical energy is available to move ions.
~It is an ion property
}

::neuron_which_ions::
Which ions mainly shape the resting membrane potential?
{
~Na⁺ and Ca²⁺
~Ca²⁺ and Cl⁻
=K⁺ and leak channels #Resting potential reflects high K⁺ permeability through leak channels.
~Na⁺ and pumps
}

::neuron_what_happens::
What happens if depolarization does not reach threshold?
{
~An action potential still occurs
~The neuron fires backward
=The voltage returns to rest #Subthreshold depolarizations decay back to resting potential.
~Na⁺ channels inactivate permanently
}

::neuron_why_are::
Why are action potentials considered active events?
{
~They require ATP directly
=They depend on voltage-gated channels #Voltage-gated channel dynamics make action potentials active processes.
~They involve diffusion only
~They are graded
}

::neuron_which_channel::
Which channel state prevents immediate reopening after a spike?
{
~Closed
~Open
=Inactivated #Inactivation temporarily prevents Na⁺ channels from reopening.
~Leaky
}

::neuron_which_property::
Which property limits the maximum firing frequency of neurons?
{
~Membrane thickness
~Channel selectivity
=Refractory period #The refractory period limits how fast neurons can fire.
~Diffusion rate
}

$CATEGORY: module_1_multi/synapse

::synapse_what_is::
What is a synapse?
{
~A continuous cytoplasmic bridge between neurons
=A specialized junction for neuronal communication #A synapse is a specialized junction where neurons communicate with other cells.
~A region of myelin insulation
~An electrical gap junction only
}

::synapse_what_separates::
What separates the presynaptic and postsynaptic neurons?
{
~Myelin sheath
=Synaptic cleft #Neurons are not physically continuous; they are separated by the synaptic cleft.
~Axon hillock
~Cytoskeleton
}

::synapse_which_component::
Which component releases neurotransmitters?
{
~Postsynaptic membrane
~Synaptic cleft
=Presynaptic terminal #Neurotransmitters are released from the presynaptic terminal.
~Dendritic spine
}

::synapse_synaptic_signaling::
Synaptic signaling is typically:
{
~Bidirectional
~Random
=Directional #Synaptic transmission is directional, from presynaptic to postsynaptic cell.
~Independent of structure
}

::synapse_what_triggers::
What triggers neurotransmitter release at the presynaptic terminal?
{
~Sodium influx
~Potassium efflux
