~Only short-term effects
~Neurotransmitter synthesis
}

::plast_adult_neurogenesis::
Adult neurogenesis occurs primarily in:
{
~Cerebral cortex
~Basal ganglia
=Hippocampus #Adult neurogenesis is restricted mainly to the hippocampus.
~Cerebellum
}

::plast_hebb_s::
Hebb’s principle states that synapses strengthen when:
{
~Neurons fire independently
=Presynaptic activity predicts postsynaptic firing #Correlated activity strengthens synaptic connections.
~Postsynaptic neurons are silent
~Activity is random
}

::plast_the_phrase::
The phrase “neurons that fire together, wire together” summarizes:
{
~Homeostatic plasticity
=Hebbian plasticity #This is the core idea of Hebbian plasticity.
~Neurogenesis
~Apoptosis
}

::plast_which_receptor::
Which receptor acts as a coincidence detector?
{
~AMPA receptor
~GABA-A receptor
=NMDA receptor #NMDA receptors require presynaptic and postsynaptic activity.
~Metabotropic glutamate receptor
}

::plast_why_is::
Why is the NMDA receptor blocked at resting potential?
{
~Chloride ions
~Calcium ions
=Magnesium ions #Magnesium blocks the NMDA channel at rest.
~Sodium ions
}

::plast_nmda_receptor::
NMDA receptor activation allows entry of:
{
~Sodium
~Chloride
=Calcium #Calcium influx triggers plasticity mechanisms.
~Potassium
}

::plast_long_term::
Long-term potentiation (LTP) is defined as:
{
~Temporary synaptic fatigue
=Persistent increase in synaptic efficacy #LTP produces long-lasting synaptic strengthening.
~Neuron proliferation
~Global network scaling
}

::plast_one_immediate::
One immediate effect of LTP is:
{
~Neuron death
~Removal of AMPA receptors
=Insertion of AMPA receptors #LTP increases AMPA receptor insertion.
~Axonal pruning
}

::plast_morphological_changes::
Morphological changes in LTP typically occur:
{
~Within milliseconds
~Within seconds
=Hours to days later #Structural plasticity stabilizes long-term changes.
~Only during development
}

::plast_long_term::
Long-term depression (LTD) involves:
{
~Increased AMPA receptor insertion
=Reduced synaptic efficacy #LTD weakens synaptic transmission.
~Neuron migration
~Increased firing rates
}

::plast_functional_ltd::
Functional LTD typically involves:
{
~Insertion of NMDA receptors
=Removal of AMPA receptors #AMPA receptor removal reduces synaptic strength.
~Axon elongation
~Increased calcium influx
}

::plast_ltp_and::
LTP and LTD together allow circuits to:
{
~Grow indefinitely
~Remain static
=Strengthen relevant and weaken irrelevant connections #Plasticity is about balance, not just strengthening.
~Eliminate all weak synapses
}

::plast_why_is::
Why is Hebbian plasticity alone unstable?
{
~It eliminates learning
=It leads to runaway excitation or silence #Unregulated Hebbian plasticity destabilizes networks.
~It prevents memory formation
~It blocks neurogenesis
}

::plast_homeostatic_plasticity::
Homeostatic plasticity primarily functions to:
{
~Encode memories
=Stabilize overall neural activity #Homeostatic mechanisms keep activity within functional ranges.
~Generate new synapses
~Eliminate variability
}

::plast_when_neural::
When neural activity is chronically high, homeostatic plasticity:
{
~Strengthens all synapses
=Weakens all synapses proportionally #Global downscaling prevents runaway excitation.
~Eliminates synapses
~Blocks firing completely
}

::plast_homeostatic_plasticity::
Homeostatic plasticity preserves:
{
~Absolute synaptic strengths
=Relative differences between synapses #Relative synaptic weights are maintained.
~Only inhibitory synapses
~Only excitatory synapses
}

::plast_who_demonstrated::
Who demonstrated adult neurogenesis in birds?
{
~Donald Hebb
~Eric Kandel
=Fernando Nottebohm #Nottebohm overturned the dogma of no adult neurogenesis.
~Santiago Ramón y Cajal
