$CATEGORY: module_1_multi/gxe

::gxe_the_original::
The original meaning of resilience comes from:
{
~Psychology
~Biology
=Metallurgy #Resilience originally referred to materials resisting force without breaking.
~Medicine
}

::gxe_in_psychology::
In psychology, resilience primarily refers to:
{
~Enduring stress without change
~Suppressing emotional responses
=Active adaptation to adversity #Psychological resilience involves active and adaptive responses.
~Genetic resistance to disease
}

::gxe_the_kauai::
The Kauai longitudinal study followed:
{
~Adults exposed to trauma
=Children born in 1955 on Kauai #Werner followed an entire birth cohort from Kauai.
~Families across generations
~Clinical psychiatric patients
}

::gxe_approximately_what::
Approximately what fraction of high-risk children in the Kauai study developed normally?
{
~Almost none
=About one third #About one third showed resilient outcomes.
~Half
~Nearly all
}

::gxe_the_kauai::
The Kauai study shifted research focus from:
{
~Genes to environment
=Risk factors to protective factors #The key shift was toward identifying protective factors.
~Brain to behavior
~Diagnosis to treatment
}

::gxe_resilience_is::
Resilience is best described as:
{
~The absence of pathology
~Passive endurance
=An active biological process #Resilience involves active molecular and circuit-level changes.
~Purely psychological coping
}

::gxe_passive_resilience::
Passive resilience refers to:
{
~Enhanced adaptive responses
=Absence of maladaptive changes #Passive resilience reflects lack of harmful responses.
~Increased plasticity
~Environmental enrichment
}

::gxe_active_resilience::
Active resilience involves:
{
~Lack of stress exposure
=Presence of adaptive plastic changes #Active resilience includes changes unique to resilient individuals.
~Reduced gene expression
~Behavioral avoidance only
}

::gxe_which_concept::
Which concept is central to both forms of resilience?
{
=Neuroplasticity #Plasticity enables adaptation to adversity.
~Neurogenesis
~Neurodegeneration
~Neural pruning
}

::gxe_the_gene::
The gene-to-disorder approach assumes:
{
~Genes act only with environment
=Linear effects of genes on disorders #This approach assumes direct gene-disorder links.
~Disorders arise without genetics
~Genes affect only endophenotypes
}

::gxe_a_major::
A major limitation of the gene-to-disorder approach was:
{
~Ethical concerns
~Poor animal models
=Replication failures #Many associations failed to replicate.
~Lack of diagnostic criteria
}

::gxe_endophenotypes_are::
Endophenotypes are defined as:
{
~Behavioral symptoms
~Environmental risk factors
=Heritable intermediate traits #Endophenotypes bridge genes and disorders.
~Clinical diagnoses
}

::gxe_the_endophenotype::
The endophenotype-to-disorder approach assumes:
{
~Genes affect diagnoses directly
=Genes have stronger effects on intermediate traits #Intermediate traits are closer to genetic action.
~Environment is irrelevant
~Endophenotypes are non-heritable
}

::gxe_the_g::
The G×E approach emphasizes:
{
~Genes alone
~Environment alone
=Their interaction #Risk emerges from gene–environment interaction.
~Random developmental noise
}

::gxe_in_a::
In a G×E framework, genes are best described as:
{
~Deterministic causes
~Inactive without environment
=Risk or sensitivity factors #Genes modulate sensitivity to environments.
~Protective only
}

::gxe_a_polymorphism::
A polymorphism is defined as a DNA variant present in:
{
~Any individual
~Less than 0.1% of the population
=More than 1% of the population #Polymorphisms are common variants.
~Only clinical populations
}

::gxe_polymorphisms_typically::
Polymorphisms typically:
{
~Cause disease directly
=Act as risk or protective factors #Their effects depend on context.
~Eliminate plasticity
~Prevent development
}

::gxe_childhood_maltreatment::
Childhood maltreatment is:
{
~A sufficient cause of antisocial behavior
~A weak risk factor
=A strong but non-deterministic risk factor #Maltreatment increases risk but does not determine outcomes.
~Irrelevant to later outcomes
}

::gxe_the_maoa::
The MAOA gene is located on the:
{
~Chromosome 1
~Y chromosome
=X chromosome #MAOA is X-linked.
~Chromosome 21
}

::gxe_maoa_encodes::
MAOA encodes an enzyme involved in the breakdown of:
{
~Glutamate
=Monoamines #MAOA degrades dopamine, serotonin, and norepinephrine.
~GABA
~Acetylcholine
}

::gxe_low_activity::
Low-activity MAOA variants result in:
{
~Faster neurotransmitter degradation
~Reduced synaptic signaling
=Prolonged monoamine action #Neurotransmitters persist longer at synapses.
~Complete enzyme loss
}

::gxe_in_the::
In the Dunedin study, antisocial behavior increased most in:
{
~High-activity MAOA individuals
=Low-activity MAOA individuals exposed to maltreatment #The effect emerged only under adversity.
~All individuals equally
~Individuals without maltreatment
}

::gxe_the_maoa::
The MAOA polymorphism alone was:
{
~Sufficient to cause antisocial behavior
~Protective
=Not sufficient to predict behavior #The environment was necessary.
~Unrelated to neurotransmission
}

::gxe_the_serotonin::
The serotonin transporter gene (5-HTT) regulates:
{
~Serotonin synthesis
~Serotonin receptor binding
=Serotonin reuptake #5-HTT controls synaptic serotonin clearance.
~Serotonin degradation
}

::gxe_the_short::
The short (s) allele of 5-HTTLPR is associated with:
{
~Higher transporter expression
=Lower transporter expression #The short allele reduces transcription.
~Faster serotonin breakdown
~Increased dopamine release
}

::gxe_in_the::
In the absence of stress, depression levels across 5-HTTLPR genotypes were:
{
~Very different
~Highest in s/s individuals
=Similar #The gene effect emerged only under stress.
~Only present in l/l individuals
}

::gxe_the_dunedin::
The Dunedin depression study showed:
{
~A main effect of genotype
~A main effect of stress only
=A significant gene–environment interaction #Stress effects depended on genotype.
~No genetic involvement
}

::gxe_the_drd::
The DRD4 gene codes for:
{
~A serotonin transporter
=A dopamine receptor #DRD4 codes for the D4 dopamine receptor.
~A dopamine enzyme
~A glutamate receptor
}

::gxe_the_drd::
The DRD4 long (L) variant is considered:
{
~Hyperfunctional
=Hypofunctional #The L variant reduces receptor efficiency.
~Inactive
~Protective only
}

::gxe_in_the::
In the alcohol experiment, L/L individuals showed:
{
~No effect of alcohol
~Less desire to drink
=Increased desire to continue drinking after alcohol #Genotype modulated alcohol effects.
~Reduced reward sensitivity
}

::gxe_early_cannabis::
Early cannabis use is associated with increased risk of:
{
~Depression only
~Anxiety disorders only
=Psychosis #Risk increases but is not universal.
~Dementia
}

::gxe_the_comt::
The COMT gene is particularly important in the:
{
~Amygdala
~Hippocampus
=Prefrontal cortex #COMT regulates dopamine in PFC.
~Cerebellum
}

::gxe_in_the::
In the cannabis working memory study, impairment was strongest in:
{
~MET/MET individuals
=VAL/VAL individuals #Cannabis effects depended on COMT genotype.
~All genotypes equally
~Only non-users
}

::gxe_the_bucharest::
The Bucharest Early Intervention Project studied:
{
~Genetic disorders
~Adult depression
=Early psychosocial deprivation #The BEI focused on institutional deprivation.
~Substance abuse
}

::gxe_the_bei::
The BEI project design allowed:
{
~Correlational inference
~Pure genetic inference
=Causal inference #Randomization allowed causal conclusions.
~Animal modeling
}

::gxe_earlier_placement::
Earlier placement into foster care resulted in:
{
~Worse outcomes
~No differences
=Better cognitive outcomes #Timing of intervention mattered.
~Only emotional benefits
}

::gxe_in_the::
In the BEI genetic moderator study, VAL/VAL children:
{
~Did not improve
=Improved the most in foster care #They benefited strongly from positive environments.
~Were always resilient
~Were unaffected by environment
}

::gxe_this_pattern::
This pattern supports the idea of:
{
~Pure vulnerability
~Genetic determinism
=Plasticity #Susceptibility applied to improvement as well.
~Random recovery
}

::gxe_the_differential::
The differential susceptibility model proposes that:
{
~Some genes only increase risk
~Genes act only under stress
=Some genotypes increase sensitivity to all environments #Plasticity variants amplify both positive and negative effects.
~Environment overrides genetics completely
}

::gxe_according_to::
According to differential susceptibility, some genes are better described as:
{
~Risk genes
~Disease genes
=Plasticity genes #They increase environmental responsiveness.
~Neutral genes
}

::gxe_a_key::
A key implication of G×E research is that:
{
~Genes cannot be changed
~Environment is irrelevant
=Improving environments can reduce risk #Prevention through environment is powerful.
~Disorders are inevitable
}

$CATEGORY: module_1_multi/epigenetics

::epigenetics_epigenetic_mechanisms::
Epigenetic mechanisms are especially relevant for understanding behavior because they:
{
~Change the DNA sequence
~Act only during embryonic development
=Allow experiences to have long-lasting biological effects #Epigenetics explains how transient experiences can produce persistent effects.
~Eliminate genetic influences
}

::epigenetics_epigenetics_was::
Epigenetics was originally developed to explain:
{
~Mental disorders
=Inheritance of traits without DNA sequence changes #Epigenetics emerged from developmental biology and cell differentiation.
~Neural signaling
~Learning and memory
}

::epigenetics_which_of::
Which of the following is NOT an epigenetic mechanism?
{
~DNA methylation
~Histone acetylation
=DNA mutation #Epigenetic mechanisms do not alter DNA sequence.
~Chromatin remodeling
}

::epigenetics_during_development::
During development, cell differentiation occurs mainly through:
{
~Loss of genes
=Epigenetic regulation of gene expression #Genes remain present but are differentially regulated.
~Random mutations
~Neuronal activity
}

::epigenetics_in_neurons::
In neurons, epigenetic changes are important because they:
{
~Are rapidly reversible
~Act only at the population level
=Provide long-term regulation at the single-cell level #Epigenetic changes can persist within individual neurons.
~Replace synaptic plasticity
}

::epigenetics_epigenetic_mechanisms::
Epigenetic mechanisms modify gene expression by acting on:
{
~mRNA stability
=Chromatin structure #They regulate accessibility of DNA to transcription machinery.
~Protein folding
~Ion channels
}

::epigenetics_chromatin_is::
Chromatin is composed of:
{
~RNA and proteins
=DNA and histone proteins #Chromatin is DNA wrapped around histones.
~Only DNA
~Only histones
}

::epigenetics_tightly_packed::
Tightly packed chromatin is typically associated with:
{
~High transcription
~Medium transcription
=Low or absent transcription #Compact chromatin restricts access to transcription machinery.
~Increased plasticity
}

::epigenetics_dna_methylation::
DNA methylation generally:
{
~Promotes transcription
=Blocks transcription #Methylation acts as a transcriptional stop signal.
~Has no effect on gene expression
~Removes histones
}

::epigenetics_studies_of::
Studies of monozygotic twins show that epigenetic patterns:
{
~Remain identical throughout life
=Diverge with different experiences #Life experiences shape epigenetic divergence.
~Depend only on genetics
~Disappear with age
}

::epigenetics_histone_modifications::
Histone modifications are best described as:
{
~Changes in DNA sequence
=Post-translational chemical modifications #They modify histone proteins after synthesis.
~Permanent gene deletions
~Random molecular noise
}

::epigenetics_histone_modifications::
Histone modifications influence gene expression mainly by:
{
~Altering RNA transcription rate directly
=Changing how tightly DNA is packed #They regulate chromatin accessibility.
~Destroying transcription factors
~Removing methyl groups from DNA
}

::epigenetics_the_concept::
The concept of a "histone code" refers to:
{
~A single dominant modification
~Random histone changes
=Combinations of histone modifications encoding regulatory information #Different combinations fine-tune gene regulation.
~Genetic mutations in histones
}

::epigenetics_histone_acetylation::
Histone acetylation typically leads to:
{
~More compact chromatin
~Reduced gene expression
=Less compact chromatin #Acetylation increases DNA accessibility.
~DNA degradation
}

::epigenetics_chronic_social::
Chronic social defeat stress is used as a model to study:
{
~Learning and memory
~Neurodevelopment
=Stress, depression-like behavior, and resilience #It models chronic psychosocial stress.
~Motor control
}

::epigenetics_in_the::
In the social defeat paradigm, stable depression-like behavior requires:
{
~A single exposure
=At least 10 days of stress #Shorter protocols are insufficient.
~Genetic manipulation
~Physical injury
}

::epigenetics_anhedonia_in::
Anhedonia in mice is commonly assessed by:
{
~Maze performance
~Food intake
=Social interaction tests #Reduced social interaction reflects anhedonia-like behavior.
~Pain sensitivity
}

::epigenetics_after_chronic::
After chronic social defeat, mice can be classified as:
{
~Normal or abnormal
~Genetically distinct
=Susceptible or resilient #Behavioral outcomes differ despite identical genetics.
~Healthy or sick
}

::epigenetics_differences_between::
Differences between susceptible and resilient mice arise mainly from:
{
~DNA mutations
=Epigenetic regulation #They belong to the same genetic strain.
~Developmental defects
~Sensory deprivation
}

::epigenetics_under_normal::
Under normal conditions, the BDNF gene in the hippocampus shows:
{
~Low expression
=Open chromatin and high expression #BDNF supports plasticity under normal conditions.
~Permanent DNA methylation
~No epigenetic regulation
}

::epigenetics_chronic_stress::
Chronic stress reduces hippocampal BDNF expression mainly by:
{
~DNA mutation
=Reduced histone acetylation #Chromatin becomes more compact.
~Increased neurogenesis
~Enhanced transcription
}

::epigenetics_reduced_hippocampal::
Reduced hippocampal BDNF leads to:
{
~Enhanced plasticity
~Increased neurogenesis
=Reduced plasticity and neurogenesis #BDNF is crucial for hippocampal function.
~Improved stress regulation
}

::epigenetics_antidepressant_treatment::
Antidepressant treatment restores BDNF expression primarily by:
{
~Removing DNA methylation
=Increasing histone acetylation #DNA methylation often persists.
~Changing DNA sequence
~Blocking transcription
}

::epigenetics_stress_induced::
